solution:
We have  \begin{align*}
(4-5i)(-5+5i) &= 4(-5) + 4(5i) -5i(-5) -5i(5i) \\
&= -20 + 20i + 25i + 25 \\
&= \boxed{5 + 45i}.
\end{align*} If $z = 4-5i,$ then \begin{align*}
|z| &= \sqrt{4^2 + (-5)^2} = \sqrt{16 + 25} = \sqrt{41}, \\
\operatorname{arg}(z) &= \tan^{-1} \left(-\frac{5}{4}\right).
\end{align*} If $z' = -5+5i,$ then \begin{align*}
|z'| &= \sqrt{(-5)^2 + 5^2} = \sqrt{25 + 25} = \sqrt{50} = 5\sqrt{2}, \\
\operatorname{arg}(z') &= \tan^{-1}(1) = \frac{\pi}{4}.
\end{align*} Thus, \begin{align*}
|z z'| &= |z||z'| = \sqrt{41} \cdot 5 \sqrt{2} = 5 \sqrt{82}, \\
\operatorname{arg}(z z') &= \operatorname{arg}(z) + \operatorname{arg}(z') = \tan^{-1}\left(-\frac{5}{4}\right) + \frac{\pi}{4}.
\end{align*} Therefore, we have \begin{align*}
z z' &= 5 \sqrt{82} \left(\cos \left(\tan^{-1}\left(-\frac{5}{4}\right) + \frac{\pi}{4}\right) + i \sin \left(\tan^{-1}\left(-\frac{5}{4}\right) + \frac{\pi}{4}\right)\right).
\end{align*} Since $\tan^{-1} \left(-\frac{5}{4}\right) + \frac{\pi}{4}$ does not have a special name, we leave the answer in that form.
